description.narrative:
(CRUDAN) Strength active citizen and system, more broadly, this action contributes to SDG 1 and 2 in Nigeria (to end poverty in allits forms everywhere and end hunger,achieve food security and improved nutrition, and promote sustainable agriculture). Italigns with the EUs joint cooperation strategy in Nigeria that targets poverty alleviation, improved capacity of state and local governments to deliver quality of services and better coherence and coordination between the three tiers of government in respect of poverty alleviation programmes.  This action is part of what EU calls the Food Security and Sustainable Agriculture (FSSA) thematic instrument under the Global Public Goods and Challenges Programme (GPGC) and it contributes to the policy commitmentthrough the component Supporting the poor and food insecure to react to crises and strengthen resilience. That component addresses in particular food insecurityincountries in post-crisis situations and will support vulnerable populations to becomemore resilient, thereby linking Relief Rehabilitation and Development. The global objective of OSAID is to enhance resilience to food shocks, chronic and acute food insecure people in post-food crisis by improving adaptation to climate change, combatingdesertification, promoting nutrition sensitive activities and policies and encouraging sustainable and resilient small scale agricultural practices. Finally, this action specifically aligns with the Agricultural Transformation Agenda (ATA) that recognizestheneed for resilience development in smallholder farming and the National Agricultural Resilience Framework (NARF) on climate change. The NARF has articulated shortand long- term strategies to reduce food and nutrition vulnerability whilst enhancing environmentalresilience and made provisions to:
-Encourage cultivation of drought tolerant crops and develop markets to support local food systems;
-Promote policiestoimprove water management;
-Promote weatherindex insurance schemes for farmers;
-Promotesocial safety net policies to reduce vulnerability, especially for women and children.
The action will complement but not overlap with the ongoing food security programmes in the target States/ LGAs supported by various bilateral and multilateral programmes suchasEU, DfID, SIDA, UNEP, IFAD, and the World Bank in Nigeria.
